{"title_page": "J.D.Y. Peel", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name         = J.D.Y. Peel\n| image        =\n| imagesize    = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = John David Yeadon Peel\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1941|11|11}}\n| birth_place  = [[Dumfries]], [[Dumfries and Galloway]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|2015|11|02|1941|11|11|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| occupation   = [[Anthropology]], [[sociology]], [[history]]\n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = [[University of Oxford]]<br/>[[London School of Economics]]\n| period       = \n| genre        = \n| subject      = [[History of Nigeria|History]] and [[religion in Nigeria]]\n| movement     = \n| notableworks = \n| spouse       = {{marriage|Jennifer Parre}}<br/>{{marriage|Anne Obigbo|2014|2015}}\n| partner      = \n| children     = \n| relatives    = \n| influences   = \n| influenced   = \n| awards       = \n| signature    = \n| website      =  \n}}\n'''J.D.Y. Peel''' {{postnominals|GBR|FBA}} (1941-2015) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[anthropology|anthropologist]], [[sociology|sociologist]] and historian of [[religion in Africa]], particularly in [[Nigeria]]. He was most notable for his studies of historical patterns of religious belief among the [[Yoruba people]]. \n\n==Biography==\nJohn David Yeadon Peel was born in [[Dumfries]], [[Scotland]] on 11 November 1941 and was educated at [[King Edward's School, Birmingham]] and [[Balliol College, Oxford]]. He gained a doctorate in [[sociology]] from the [[London School of Economics]] (LSE) on [[African-initiated church|Independent Churches]] in [[Nigeria]]. He held a succession of academic posts at universities in the United Kingdom and Nigeria, finishing his career at the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] (SOAS).{{sfn|SOAS|2015}} As well as African subjects, he retained an interest in the [[history of sociology]] and authored a biography of the sociologist [[Herbert Spencer]] in 1971 and taught [[social theory]].{{sfn|RAI|2016}}\n\nPeel was one of the first scholars to examine the theology and organisation of African independent churches. [[Paul Gifford]] wrote that \"[his] thrust was generally [[Max Weber|Weberian]], insisting that religion could not be reduced to material or class interests\".{{sfn|SOAS|2015}} He published three cumulative works on religious change among the [[Yoruba people]] in Nigeria between 1968 and 2015, exploring aspects of [[Christianity]], [[Islam]] and [[Yoruba religion|indigenous belief]] among the Yoruba from the pre-colonial period onwards. [[Robin W. G. Horton]]'s \"intellectualist theory\" of African religion was first set out in a review of Peel's 1968 volume.{{sfn|SOAS|2015}}\n\nPeel was a fellow and vice-president (1999-2000) of the [[British Academy]] and president of the [[African Studies Association of the United Kingdom]] (ASAUK; 1996\u201398).{{sfn|SOAS|2015}} He was awarded the ASAUK's \"Distinguished Africanist\" award in 2015. He was editor of ''[[Africa (journal)|Africa: Journal of the International Africa Institute]]'' from 1979 to 1986.{{sfn|RAI|2016}} He died in [[London]] on 2 November 2015.{{sfn|RAI|2016}}\n\n==Selected publications==\n*''Aladura: a Religious Movement among the Yoruba'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1968)\n*''Ijeshas and Nigerians: the Incorporation of a Yoruba Kingdom 1890s-1970s'' (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1984)\n*''Religious Encounter and the Making of the Yoruba'' (Bloomington: Indiana University Press, 2000)\n*''Christianity, Islam and the Orisa: Comparative Studies of Three Religions in Interaction and Transformation'' (Oakland: University of California Press, 2015).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite web|ref={{harvid|SOAS|2015}}|last1=Gifford|first1=Paul|last2=Rathbone|first2=Richard|title=Professor J D Y Peel|date=10 November 2015|website=School of Oriental and African Studies|url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/news/